AUGUSTUS had been in Gaul, where he had put a stop to the progress of the Sicambri, and confirmed the conquests of Tiberius and Drusus over the Rhaeti and Vindelici. His return was expect- ed with much impatience at Rome, where a magnificent triumph was preparing for him. On this occasion Antonius Julius, then praetor of the city, requested Horace to write a Pindaric ode in honor of Augustus, Our poet confesses himself unequal to the task, and tells Antonius that he can much better perform it him- se1f3 while at the same time, as his commentators say, he surpass- ed even Pindar.
